<page>
 <p><m>\textbf {Theorem}</m></p>
 <ul>
  <li>
    <p>An <m>m \times n</m> matrix <m>U</m> has orthonormal columns if and only if<m>U^T U = I_n</m>.</p>
  </li>
 </ul>
 <p><m>\textbf {Definition}</m></p>
 <ul>
  <li>
    <p>An <m>\textbf {orthogonal matrix}</m> is a square invertible matrix <m>U</m> so that <m>U^T U = I</m>.</p>
  </li>
 </ul>
 <p>Note: </p>
 <ul>
  <li>
    <p>In other words, an <m>\textbf {orthogonal matrix}</m> is a square matrix with <m>\textbf {orthonormal columns}</m>.</p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>There is no name for matrices that have columns that are orthogonal but orthonormal</p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>If <m>U</m> is <m>m \times n</m>, can <m>U</m> have orthonormal columns when <m>n > m</m>?</p>
  </li>
 </ul>
 <m></m><p></p><m></m><p></p><m></m><p></p><m></m><p></p><m></m><p></p><m></m><p></p>
 <m></m><p></p><m></m><p></p><m></m><p></p><m></m><p></p><m></m><p></p><m></m><p></p>
 <p><m>\textbf {18.2.1 Properties of Matrices with Orthonormal Columns}</m></p>
 <ol marker="1.">
  <li>
    <m>\|\vec{Ux}\| = \|\vec{x}\|</m>
  </li>
  <li>
    <m>(\vec{Ux}) \cdot (\vec{Uy}) = \vec{x} \cdot \vec{y}</m>
  </li>
  <li>
    <m>(\vec{Ux}) \cdot (\vec{Uy}) = 0</m> if and only if <m>\vec{x} \cdot \vec{y} = 0</m>
  </li>
</ol>
<p>These properties tell us that the mapping <m>\vec {x} \to U \vec{x}</m> preserves lngth and orthogonality.</p>
</page>
